Many here aren't good readers. Add in ADHD issues, and it limits what writers put out there; today's readers are tomorrow's writers.

>"Brace yourself if you keep reading," Anon said.

>"Brace yourself if you keep reading." Anon said.

>"Brace yourself if you keep reading." Anon hated being negative about free content, but the latest chapter had rubbed him the wrong way.

tl;dr no one expects perfect MLA/Chicago editing, but a cleaner story always reads better.

Anonymous Thu 08 Sep 2022 03:36:23 No.50767924 Report
Quoted By:
>>50766279
One of the things that helped me was working face-to-face with other writers and beta/first reading for them.
Doing that ethically, as well as knowing that you're proving your ability just as much by how you treat others as what you've laid on the table does up the stakes.
The other valuable bit is learning that you're not going to satisfy everyone, nor are you going to agree with the deliberate choices another writer made. Talking shop in a non-confrontational way will sharpen your own editing skills, and doubly so if you're doing it back and forth in private (so that you can really dig into things)

And last, it feels damned good to apply what you've learned, especially when a writer's story gets even better on a mechanical level.

>I think critiquing grammar takes more effort, because it usually consists of pointing out every single mistake, with context.
That's a fair point, but if I'm doing something for review and there's multiple problems, I'm pointing it out once or maybe twice with examples and leaving it while mentioning this problem exists in other places too. A novice needs to know what to look for when critiquing their own writing so they can develop self-editing skills.
When I do full reviews, I take as much as I can from the breadth of the story, which means focusing on storytelling elements as much as the technical ones. I think most authors prefer a wide range of comments over exclusive nitpicking about grammar or spelling. I only have so much time to critique others, especially when I'm juggling that with my own writing time and my other responsibilites.
